  <h2 class="sec" id="s1"><span class="n">1.</span>What MidBid is — and what it is not</h2>
  <p>1.1 MidBid is an <strong>online, blind-bid negotiation and mediation support tool</strong>. It gives two parties to a dispute a private, structured way to exchange confidential settlement figures and to discover whether a settlement is achievable, without either party revealing their figures to the other.</p>
  <p>1.2 In a typical case, one party (the “Claimant”, who is owed money) creates a case and invites the other party (the “Respondent”, who owes money). Each party privately sets three confidential figures — their <strong>Ideal</strong> outcome, their <strong>Target</strong>, and their <strong>Walk-away</strong> point. The Platform compares these figures on the server only and tells each party, through neutral signals, how close the two positions are. Neither party ever sees the other’s figures or the precise gap between them. A settlement is reached only when <strong>both</strong> parties have approved.</p>
  <p>1.3 <strong>MidBid is technology, not a person, a representative, or a decision-maker.</strong> It does not negotiate on your behalf, take sides, or determine any party’s rights or liabilities. Any settlement is reached by the parties themselves.</p>
  <p>1.4 <strong>MidBid is not an arbitration service and issues no arbitral award or binding determination.</strong> Where the Platform generates a draft settlement agreement from an agreed figure, that document is a draft record produced automatically for the parties’ convenience. It is not legal advice, not a court order or arbitral award, and has no legal effect unless and until the parties review it, agree its terms, and execute it in accordance with applicable law.</p>
  <p>1.5 <strong>MidBid is not a law firm and does not provide legal advice.</strong> Using the Platform does not create any solicitor–client, attorney–client, or other professional relationship. We recommend you obtain independent legal advice before creating a case, submitting any figure, or signing any settlement document.</p>

  <h2 class="sec" id="s2"><span class="n">2.</span>Definitions</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>“Case”</strong> — a single dispute created on the Platform, identified by a title and an amount in dispute.</li>
    <li><strong>“Amount in dispute”</strong> — the monetary value entered when creating a Case, against which figures are set.</li>
    <li><strong>“Figure” / “Anchor”</strong> — a confidential monetary value submitted by a party (Ideal, Target, or Walk-away).</li>
    <li><strong>“Settlement”</strong> — a figure that both parties have approved through the Platform.</li>
    <li><strong>“Blind process”</strong> — the principle that a party’s Figures are never disclosed to the other party.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="sec" id="s3"><span class="n">3.</span>Eligibility</h2>
  <p>3.1 The Platform is available only to persons who are at least <strong>18 years old</strong> and who have the legal capacity to enter into binding contracts.</p>
  <p>3.2 By using the Platform you represent that you meet these requirements and that any information you provide is true, accurate, current and complete. The Platform is not intended for, and must not be used by, minors.</p>

  <h2 class="sec" id="s4"><span class="n">4.</span>Your account</h2>
  <p>4.1 To use most features you must register using a valid email address and a password. You are responsible for keeping your credentials confidential and for all activity under your account.</p>
  <p>4.2 Notify us promptly at <a href="mailto:hello@midbid.org">hello@midbid.org</a> if you suspect unauthorised use of your account, discover a security vulnerability, or lose access to your credentials.</p>
  <p>4.3 You agree to keep your account information up to date.</p>

  <h2 class="sec" id="s5"><span class="n">5.</span>How the Service works</h2>
  <p>5.1 <strong>Creating and joining a case.</strong> A party creates a Case by entering a title, the amount in dispute, and the other party’s email address, then shares a private invitation link. The other party joins by following that link and registering or signing in.</p>
  <p>5.2 <strong>Setting figures.</strong> Each party privately sets their Ideal, Target and Walk-away figures. These are visible only to the party who set them and are processed confidentially as described in clause 6 and in the Privacy Policy.</p>
  <p>5.3 <strong>Signals, not numbers.</strong> The Platform may display neutral coaching messages and a proximity indicator describing, in general terms, how close the parties are. These signals are generated automatically and <strong>never disclose the other party’s figures or the exact gap.</strong></p>
  <p>5.4 <strong>Reaching a settlement.</strong> Where the parties’ positions meet or fall within the applicable threshold, either party may approve. A Settlement is recorded only when <strong>both</strong> parties have approved. Changing your figure after approving withdraws that approval.</p>
  <p>5.5 <strong>Settlement figure.</strong> Where a Settlement is reached, the recorded figure is calculated automatically by the Platform (for example, as the midpoint of the parties’ binding figures) and rounded as the Service specifies. Please review the recorded figure before relying on it.</p>
  <p>5.6 <strong>Draft settlement agreement.</strong> Once a Settlement is recorded, the Platform may make available a draft settlement agreement reflecting the agreed figure. Clause 1.4 applies. It is your responsibility, and the other party’s, to review it, take independent legal advice, make any necessary amendments, and execute it.</p>
  <p>5.7 <strong>Availability.</strong> We aim to keep the Platform available but do not guarantee that it will be uninterrupted, timely, secure or error-free, and we may modify, suspend or discontinue any part of the Service at any time.</p>

  <h2 class="sec" id="s6"><span class="n">6.</span>Confidentiality and the blind process</h2>
  <p>6.1 <strong>Your figures are confidential.</strong> We do not disclose a party’s Ideal, Target or Walk-away figures to the other party. Only the neutral signals described in clause 5.3 are shared.</p>
  <p>6.2 <strong>Without prejudice.</strong> Settlement discussions through the Platform are intended to be confidential and conducted on a without-prejudice basis, so far as applicable law allows. You agree not to rely on, disclose, or seek to introduce in any proceedings the figures, signals or communications generated through the Platform, except a concluded and executed settlement agreement, or as required by law.</p>
  <p>6.3 These obligations do not prevent disclosure required by law, regulation, a court, or a competent authority.</p>

